text: I went and saw John Wick a couple of days ago and was pleasantly surprised at how good it was. It's easily the best ACTION movie this year.  The action scenes were absolutely phenomenal. (They didn't use any of that shaky cam BS that most action movies use) Also, the choreography was easily some of the best I've seen and had my eyes GLUED to the screen. It was nice seeing Keanu Reeves kicking ass again.  The story was simple and straightforward and unlike a lot of other action movies these days, it doesn't insult your intelligence. (Some of the scenes actually brought a tear to my eye)  It also had some surprisingly funny moments that had my theater laughing out loud.  If you wanna have a good time at the movie theater, GO SEE JOHN WICK. You will not be disappointed.¬†

text: As much as I like Keanu Reeves, this movie was a huge letdown. I came into it not expecting anything, though there were plenty of things wrong with this movie, and it's loaded with scenes that blatantly don't make sense. The only thing well done about it is the action choreography, which is incredibly well done. Everything else just falls flat because there's little plot to hold onto, the characters are not really all that interesting, and the jokes went over your head. It was trying to be similar to The Transporter, or any other action mixed with comedy but it really didn't get there. Every other movie Keanu Reeves made was great, even the one's that people think are bad but this one just doesn't match up. I don't understand why this movie got such extremely high ratings. John Wick would have been better if it was taken seriously as a film, though clearly no one took it seriously and everything felt rushed.¬†

text: when the movie started out basically ripping off the classic and brilliant opening of 'double indemnity,' one of the best movie openings in all of cinema, i had to suppress my skepticism. fortunately, though, it turned out to be mostly fun, a graphic novel on the screen where my biggest complaint was the small subtitles and lack of naked women. but, the body count was in the 80's, and that's, ah, 'impressive' all on its own, more than well-enough to qualify for brainless entertainment (most of the brains get splattered). a B-movie? you betcha, but there hardly isn't a minute spent being bored.¬†  ya gotta give these movies a pass and not look for any greatness. it's funner to try to find the homages than attempt a real analysis of any ridiculous themes ~ the uber macho-ness either does it for you or it doesn't. good ol' fashioned revenge flicks work for me, particularly in this era of movies when everything seems to be oh-so-serious and geared for the young female market sector of vapid filmmaking, while marvel seems to be the only ones making fun movies right now and actually succeeding at it.¬†  sometimes us guys just need a release, and, imo, this is it. still could have used some naked women, but, meh, you can't have everything all the time, eh?¬†

text: Action packed adventure with a lone gunman's quest for revenge. I have seen this film twice and was drawn in with Keanu Reeves in the lead, he is awesome in this action thriller that had me glued to the screen. Wick was created with two great stunt directors (David Leitch and Chad Stahelski), as this movie rocks with action.  The film starts with the death of Wick‚Äôs wife and the introduction of a beagle puppy, the adorable Daisy was a gift from Wick‚Äôs deceased wife. Russian thugs break into Wick‚Äôs house because they want to steal his classic Mustang, then mercilessly beat him as well as kill his dog.  What these young thugs don‚Äôt realize is that Wick is a retired hit man with a frightening reputation. Wick's former employer, Russian mafioso Viggo Tarasov (Michael Nyqvist), is the father of the ringleader of the raid to steal his car and kill his dog, Alfie Allen from Game of Thrones.¬†  Nyqvist is positively Putinesque, cruel and menacing with his heavy Russian accent and squinting eyes. When he‚Äôs not yelling or pounding people, he sits by his fireplace singing Russian folk songs.  Reeves, with shaggy hair and a three-piece suit, plays the introverted assassin well, it‚Äôs easy to root for a grieving husband who has just lost his devoted pet. John Wick goes the distance and beyond with the films increased carnage threshold. Brawls throughout each sequence attempts to outdo the last. John Wick has a more interesting storyline and better drama than most that draws you in and never let's go, I highly recommend this film as one of the best action films I have seen in years.
